args: One day, Emma was asked to support a boy from\na wealthy family in his studies. At first, she was\nfired up for the task, but after she arrived...
YOU CAN DO IT! I KNOW YOU CAN!\nOPEN THAT BOOK AND START TO CRAM!
TESTS ARE FUN! TESTS ARE GRE... Huh?
I hate it when people tell me I\ncan do stuff, so just go already!
Whaaat?! What did I do wrong?!
...So yeah, it was pretty much a disaster.
Now I understand why you returned\nhome looking so very low.
I guess everyone is putting a ton\nof pressure on the poor kid.

Apparently, his parents have super-high
standards and think he's just slacking.
So when I told him he could do it,
he sorta...took it the wrong way.
Sounds like yer cheers went down like\nan old bucket'a warm milk. Sorry, kid.
It was stupid. I mean, I know some people\ndon't like to hear how ＂they can do it,＂\nbut I went ahead and said it anyway.
I haven't grown at all if I'm making\nthe same dumb mistake twice...
Yep. Biggest mistake I ever made.
See, I've always loved encouraging people,\neven when I was little—and my parents\nalways told me I was great at it.

So I started to think that telling people
they COULD do something—and then
cheering them on to DO that thing—
was a good idea in all circumstances.
Boy howdy, was I ever wrong.

I had a friend who hit a rough patch,
so of course I told her to do her best.
Welp, that just ended up piling even
MORE pressure on her.
In the end, an older knight had to sort\nout the situation between us. I'll always\nremember what she said to me...
Rather than dwelling on this mistake,\nyou should devote your energy to\nhelping those you have yet to meet.
Do not wallow in your pity;\nlift others from their own instead.
They made me realize cheering people up\nwas my mission in life.
And I also realized I had to tailor my\nmessage to each individual person.
But now I've gone and done exactly the\nopposite of that like a big old dummy...
I think I understand you a bit more now.
And I also think your next action is clear.
If telling that boy to do his best doesn't\nwork, you'll just have to find some other\nway to encourage him.
Huh. Well, I suppose I could...
Oh, I know! I'll tell him NOT to do his best!
Okay then. I'll tell him to do his best,\nbut I'll do it SUPER quietly.
I believe the words are the issue,\nnot the volume.
Fine then! I'll just do the work for him!
But you won't give up, right?
Of course not! I'm gonna crack this nut\nif it's the last thing I ever do.
I'll think of something. I totally will!
Hey, so I'm sorry about yesterday and junk,\nbut today I'm gonna cheer you on right.
How? By telling me to do my best and\nthen claiming my best isn't enough?
If that's what you're here for, just go.
But I'm NOT gonna tell you to do your best!
Nope! I'm just going to sit here all quiet.\nSee, 'cause I already know you're doing\nyour best, so you don't need me to tell you!
So just act like I'm not here, okay?\nOh, but if you DO need something,\nI'm totally ready to help.
(Ah! He's struggling! Time to tell him\nhe can do... Wait, no!)
Ahem! Um, so if there's something you\ndon't get or whatever, maybe I can help?
Yeah, okay. This part is confusing...
So does this make sense to you?
Yep! Just read this section here, okay?\nI think it'll really help you.
N-nothing! I'm just gonna be quiet again.
Aw, I'm really proud of you!
I don't care about your grades—I care\nabout how hard you tried just now.
You didn't let the difficult problems get\nyou down, and you listened to my advice\nwhenever you were confused.
You were putting a ton of effort in,\nwhich is WAY better than some grade!
My parents never watch me that closely.\nWhy did you?
'Cause I came here to encourage you!
Finding your good points and praising\nyou for them is a huge part of that.
So, um...will you come back tomorrow?
I did it, guys! I encouraged him!

Well, I just thought about what someone
who was trying really hard would want me
to do, and also what I'D want someone to
do if it was me in that position.
I figured I'd want someone to just\nnotice how hard I was trying already,\nso that's what I did.
I've learned a lot from this, actually.\nNow I know how to encourage people\nwithout just saying ＂you can do it.＂
Then you should be even more successful\nwith your life's work going forward.
You know, it makes me happy that you\nguys all pay attention to me like that.
Just wait until you see my new cheers!
